    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>The <strong>Local Teaser Pack</strong> is a Google search result format — a variant of the standard Local Pack — that displays photos and price ranges for hotels and restaurants alongside standard local business information. It appears for high-visual-intent local queries where images and pricing are key to a searcher's click decision, primarily for accommodation and dining searches.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary categories</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Hotels &amp; Restaurants</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Extra elements</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Photos + Price range</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most local businesses compete in the standard 3-pack with text-only listings. Hotels and restaurants get an enhanced version where visual content and price signals are displayed directly in search results — before any click occurs. For these categories, GBP photo quality and price range accuracy translate directly into click-through rate.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is the Local Teaser Pack?</h2>
        <p>The Local Teaser Pack is Google's enhanced local result format for visual and price-sensitive local searches. Where the standard Local Pack shows business name, star rating, address, and hours, the Teaser Pack adds:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Photo thumbnail:</strong> A representative image pulled from Google Business Profile photos — typically an exterior shot for hotels or a signature dish for restaurants.</li>
          <li><strong>Price range indicator:</strong> The $, $$, or $$$ price range set in GBP, displayed visibly in the listing so searchers can filter by budget before clicking.</li>
          <li><strong>Standard GBP data:</strong> Rating, review count, address, hours, and website link remain present as in the standard Local Pack.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>The format is triggered by Google's query intent classification. Searches with strong visual and transactional intent — "hotels near Times Square," "best sushi restaurant downtown," "romantic restaurant for anniversary" — are more likely to trigger the teaser format than generic service searches.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Teaser Pack vs. standard Local Pack</div>
          <p>The Local Teaser Pack is not a separate ranking system — it is the same Local Pack with enhanced display elements. The same relevance, distance, and prominence signals determine which 3 businesses appear. The Teaser Pack format is Google's decision based on query type; the business cannot explicitly request it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why the Local Teaser Pack matters</h2>
        <p>For hotels and restaurants, the Teaser Pack transforms local search from a text-based competition into a visual one. Four reasons it matters:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Visual thumbnail drives first impressions.</strong> A hotel with a stunning lobby photo or a restaurant with high-quality food photography attracts the eye before the searcher reads any text. Low-quality, blurry, or irrelevant photos lose clicks to competitors whose images look more inviting.</li>
          <li><strong>Price range filtering happens before clicking.</strong> A searcher looking for a budget hotel sees $, $$, and $$$ indicators and self-selects. This pre-click filter means the traffic you receive is better qualified — a $ restaurant listing won't attract clicks from diners looking for a fine dining experience, reducing irrelevant traffic.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive differentiation in a 3-slot format.</strong> Three businesses share the teaser pack. The one with the most compelling photo wins the proportionally largest share of clicks — regardless of review count or rating differences between the 3.</li>
          <li><strong>GBP photo recency is a ranking signal.</strong> Google favors GBP listings with fresh, recently uploaded photos. Regular photo updates for hotels and restaurants improve both search visibility and the quality of the thumbnail Google selects to display.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How the Local Teaser Pack works</h2>
        <p>The Teaser Pack functions on the same underlying mechanism as the standard Local Pack with additional display logic:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Query classification</span><br>
          "best Italian restaurant near me" <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">High visual + transactional intent detected</span><br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Teaser Pack format triggered<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># For each of the 3 Local Pack results:</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Thumbnail</span>  <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">Best photo from GBP (auto-selected by Google)</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Price range</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">$ / $$ / $$$ from GBP attributes</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Rating</span>     <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">Aggregate Google review score</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Address</span>   <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">Verified GBP address</span>
        </div>

        <p>Google auto-selects the thumbnail from available GBP photos. The business cannot designate a specific photo for the teaser — Google's algorithm picks what it considers most representative. However, uploading more high-quality photos increases the probability that the selected thumbnail is a strong one.</p>

