        <h2 id="examples">Local Teaser Pack in practice</h2>

        <h3>1. Hotel category — visual competition</h3>
        <p>For a query like "hotels near downtown Chicago," the Teaser Pack shows 3 hotels with room or lobby thumbnails and price ranges. A hotel with professional photography showing elegant rooms in the $$ range attracts searchers shopping for mid-tier accommodation. The same hotel's competitor showing a blurry exterior photo loses clicks even if it has a higher review average. The visual layer changes the competitive dynamic entirely from the standard Local Pack.</p>

        <h3>2. Restaurant category — cuisine photo impact</h3>
        <p>A 12-location restaurant chain saw a 60% increase in Google Business Profile impressions after auditing and replacing GBP photos across all locations with professional food photography. For restaurant teaser pack appearances, the food photo is the primary conversion driver — it communicates cuisine type, quality level, and visual appeal faster than any text element.</p>

        <h3>3. Optimizing the price range attribute</h3>
        <p>A boutique hotel priced at $$$$ (luxury tier) saw lower click-through rates in the Teaser Pack for mid-range queries. After verifying that the price range was correctly set in GBP, the hotel's teaser appearances shifted toward high-intent luxury queries — fewer total impressions, but dramatically higher conversion rate from clicks to bookings. Accurate price range settings improve lead quality even when they reduce total impression volume.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local Teaser Pack vs. standard Local Pack</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>When you see the Teaser Pack</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Hotels and accommodation searches</li>
              <li>Restaurant and dining queries</li>
              <li>High visual intent ("best," "romantic," "nice")</li>
              <li>Category searches with clear pricing tiers</li>
              <li>Searches where photos influence decisions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>When you see the standard Local Pack</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Service business queries (plumber, dentist)</li>
              <li>Emergency or utility searches</li>
              <li>B2B service queries</li>
              <li>Searches where price varies too widely to display</li>
              <li>Professional service categories</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">5 best practices for the Local Teaser Pack</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Upload professional photos regularly.</strong> Google favors GBP listings with recent, high-quality photos. For restaurants, upload food photography monthly. For hotels, upload seasonal room and amenity shots. Aim for minimum 20 photos in your GBP with at least 5 added in the last 90 days.</li>
          <li><strong>Set your price range attribute accurately.</strong> Under-pricing (marking a $$$ restaurant as $$) attracts budget seekers who leave without purchasing and drives up bounce signals. Over-pricing repels your actual audience. Accurate pricing creates better-qualified traffic.</li>
          <li><strong>Make exterior shots strong.</strong> Google often selects an exterior or entry photo for the thumbnail. Make sure your building exterior is photographed well — signage clear, entrance inviting, good lighting.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimize GBP categories precisely.</strong> The primary GBP category determines query eligibility for the Teaser Pack format. A hotel must have "Hotel" as primary category, not "Accommodation" or "Lodging." Restaurants need the specific cuisine type as a secondary category to appear for cuisine-specific queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Maintain strong review velocity.</strong> All three Local Pack positions are determined by standard local ranking factors — the Teaser Pack format doesn't change that. Reviews, NAP consistency, and GBP completeness still determine whether you appear in the 3-box at all.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — ignoring photo curation</div>
          <p>Many hotel and restaurant owners upload photos once at GBP setup and never update them. Google's algorithm deprioritizes stale photo libraries in both teaser thumbnail selection and overall GBP freshness signals. A competitor uploading 5 new photos per month will consistently get better thumbnail selections than one with the same 10 photos from 2021.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Local Teaser Pack mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>No price range set in GBP</strong> — Without a price range attribute, the Teaser Pack listing appears incomplete. Set the range that reflects your actual average spend per person.</li>
          <li><strong>Generic or low-quality photos</strong> — Stock photography or blurry phone shots lose the visual competition to competitors with professional photography.</li>
          <li><strong>Wrong primary GBP category</strong> — Using "Food" instead of "Italian Restaurant" reduces query-specific Teaser Pack appearances for cuisine searches.</li>
          <li><strong>Neglecting review recency</strong> — The 3 businesses showing in the Teaser Pack are still determined by standard local ranking signals. Declining reviews or review velocity drops the listing out of the pack regardless of photo quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Not checking the mobile view</strong> — Teaser Pack thumbnails display differently on mobile vs. desktop. Check how your selected photo appears at mobile thumbnail size before setting it as your primary GBP image.</li>
        </ul>

